<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/427580-kitty"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1421939728i/427580._UX100_CR0,30,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/427580-kitty">Kitty</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    I like Krysti's answer. I also felt that the book did not develop Edgar as a believable character-- and much as I would have wanted to feel "attached"<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    I like Krysti's answer. I also felt that the book did not develop Edgar as a believable character-- and much as I would have wanted to feel "attached" to him, I didn't. I felt the book "used" Edgar to set forth interesting information about Burma, about pianos, and to critique British imperialism. Once it became clear that a piano tuner, i.e. metaphorical helper to enable using music for peace, was a traitor and peace was a hopeless cause, there is no more reason to go on with the story. Any love story that might have developed with Khin Myo wasn't really the focus. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
