    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_96814561" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/96814561" />
    <a title="Kate" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/643652-kate"><img alt="Kate" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604027937p2/643652.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/96814561?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kate" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kate" href="/user/show/643652-kate">Kate</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer96814561" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2983268144535241780">Oh, man! It&apos;s been awhile since I read a truly great adventure story (since Gil Adamson&apos;s &apos;The Outlander&apos;, actually) and this pulled me in immediately. I just finished it last night and I have that feeling where I don&apos;t want to start another book just yet; this story is still sinking in for me. I need to give it a few days to settle. That&apos;s just good book manners, right?<br/><br/>Anyway... the book follows a middle-aged British piano tuner named Edward on his summoned tuning job to the wild and unstable j</span>
  <span id="freeText2983268144535241780" style="display:none">Oh, man! It's been awhile since I read a truly great adventure story (since Gil Adamson's 'The Outlander', actually) and this pulled me in immediately. I just finished it last night and I have that feeling where I don't want to start another book just yet; this story is still sinking in for me. I need to give it a few days to settle. That's just good book manners, right?<br /><br />Anyway... the book follows a middle-aged British piano tuner named Edward on his summoned tuning job to the wild and unstable jungles of Burma in the late 1800s. Edward is a lot like me, which is, I think, why I liked the protagonist so much despite our obvious differences. He's quiet, he's an observer - he has a lot of thoughts about the world around him but he has a hard time expressing them verbally. <br /><br />For this being Mason's first novel (and he's a doctor to boot!), I was extremely impressed with his prose. It's not your typical adventure story: here's our guy, then this happens to him, then this, then WOW, this! The end. No,not here - the plot often comes second to the emotions of the protagonist, and the chosen words work so well. There is such beauty in this story, and without giving anything away I will only tell you that it's a story at once exciting, and moving, and beautiful, and sad. I only hope Mason continues to write.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2983268144535241780" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

